   <info>
      <title>Archi StyledHtml module</title>
      <pubdate>2012-04-17</pubdate>
      <abstract>
         <itemizedlist>
            <listitem>You have designed something, you have the Archimate model on it. But you have to create a documentation in the form requested by your client.</listitem>
            <para/>
            <listitem>You are designing something complex. You want to make sure that you have thought about all aspects and interdependencies.</listitem>
            <para/>
            <listitem>You work with junior architects or developers. You are tired of checking their models for trivial errors and omissions.</listitem>
            <para/>
            <listitem>You are doing detailed design, and it is boring to do the trivial task of converting the model to config file by hand.</listitem>
         </itemizedlist>
         <para/>If any of the above happens, this module and the underlying concepts are developed for you.<para/>This module makes possible to <itemizedlist>
            <para/>
            <listitem> define and document enterprise architecture policies</listitem>
            <para/>
            <listitem>check architecture models against those policies</listitem>
            <para/>
            <listitem>define documentation styles for various stakeholders, and generate those documentations from the model</listitem>
            <para/>
            <listitem>generate configuration and code directly from the model</listitem>
         </itemizedlist>
         <para/>This model tries to fulfill multiple purposes:<para/>- Show how Archimate can be used in the goovernance of IT<para/>- Document the styledhtml Archi module<para/>- Serve as an example for both of the above<para/>- The webpage of the styledhtml module is generated from it. See <link xlink:href="http://archistyledhtml.sourceforge.net/"
               xrefstyle="what?"
               href="http://archistyledhtml.sourceforge.net/">http://archistyledhtml.sourceforge.net/</link>
         <para/>You can find user documentation in the Use Cases section.</abstract>
   </info>
   <section id="Business">
      <title>Business</title>
      <para/>
      <section id="1. Introduction">
         <title>1. Introduction</title>
         <para>This module is mainly about two things.<para/>One is to create reports from your Archimate model for the different stakeholders. If you are interested in this part, just jump to use cases, where you can find the user documentation.<para/>The other thing is to implement Archimate Extensions. You can find some introductory text here, and an example implementation in the "Sample policy" section.<para/>To see some of the possible avenues it would open, see "Possible enhancements"</para>
         <section id="1. Quick howto">
            <title>1. Quick howto</title>
            <para>This introduction is for the impatient, who just wants to generate documentation from an already existing Archi model.<para/>
               <itemizedlist>	
                  <listitem>Download the Archi Styledhtml distribution from <link xlink:href="http://sourceforge.net/projects/archistyledhtml/files/"
                           xrefstyle="what?"
                           href="http://sourceforge.net/projects/archistyledhtml/files/">http://sourceforge.net/projects/archistyledhtml/files/</link>
                  </listitem>    
                  <listitem>Extract it to a directory, as you would do with a vanilla Archi.</listitem>	
                  <listitem>Start the Archi executable in the extracted folder.</listitem>    
                  <listitem>Set a property for the model named <emphasis role="bold">report:part</emphasis> with the value <emphasis role="bold">all</emphasis>. </listitem>    
                  <listitem>Go to Edit/Preferences/Styled Export</listitem>   
                  <listitem>Push the "Install provided styles" button. Choose a folder to install the styles to.</listitem>		
                  <listitem>For stylesheet location, choose docbookandhtml.style from the folder where you have put the styles to.</listitem>         
                  <listitem>For output dir, choose a folder where you want the generated documentation to go. You might also want to check the "don't ask for location" checkbox"</listitem>	
                  <listitem>Choose file/Export/model to Styled HTML....</listitem>    
                  <listitem>Congratulations, you have a documentation generated! It is called index.html in the folder you have choosen. Take a look at it with your web browser.</listitem>   
                  <listitem>Now you can continue to explore other possibilities of the module. There are plenty of them</listitem>
               </itemizedlist>
            </para>
         </section>
      </section>
