         <section id="2. Modeling">
            <title>2. Modeling</title>
            <para>In the modeling phase, you describe something (the thing which is modeled) based on some ontology (the metamodel), resulting in a model.<para/>The Archimate methodology gives us a metamodel, which is directly useable with Archi. However often you need a metamodel more detailed than that.</para>
            <section id="1. Simple uses">
               <title>1. Simple uses</title>
               <para>For simple uses you don't even need a metamodel.</para>
               <section id="Creating docbook (and html) documentation">
                  <title>Creating docbook (and html) documentation</title>
                  <para>In some cases you just want to create a documentation which contains all, or some parts of the model.<para/>The docbook style - which is the successor of the structured style - does just that for you.<para/>There are actually two style files shipped: docbook.style creates index.docbook and docbookandhtml.style creates index.docbook and index.html.<para/>The documentation will contain the directories as docbook sections, with the diagrams first, then all the contained elements in a table as rows. The element documentation contains the element properties, except the ones known by the style and objectClass.<para/>The style is able to convert a very limited subset of html markup in the documentation to docbook (and then html). Beware that anything looking like html and not in that subset is silently omitted from the output. As too much element documentation means too few modeling, I won't go into more details, see unescape.xslt. If you really need more, please submit a working github pull request with a test case and I might include it.<para/>The style is customizable in two ways:<para/>
                     <itemizedlist>
                        <para/>
                        <listitem>model properties: there are properties which define which parts of the model will be actually generated. With the unmodified style, you should set the <emphasis role="bold">report:part</emphasis> property to <emphasis role="bold">all</emphasis> for the model or a directory. </listitem>
                        <para/>
                        <listitem>stylesheet properties: if you open the style file with a text editor, you will see a line containing the name of the xml stylesheet (docbook.xslt) doing the bulk of the work, and some parameters passed to the stylesheet. These are customizable using any text editor. I recommend saving the style file in another name in the same directory before that.</listitem>
                     </itemizedlist>
                     <para/>If you would need any more customisation of the style, please file a bug report.</para>
                  <section id="model properties for docbook">
                     <title>model properties for docbook</title>
                     <para/>
                     <table class="elementtable">
                        <tr>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">copy-image</td>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">inserts a diagram to where it is referenced</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td> </td>
                           <td/>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">from-folder</td>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">This property holds the id of a folder, and folders can be marked with it.<para/>All elements from the referenced folder will be added to the documentation of the referring folder, but diagrams, sketches and folders.<para/>Yes, it is the id of the model element which is a bit complicated to figure out (you should look at the model's xml). It does not change if you change the name of the element, and it is not ambigous. If you can come up with a better way, and you actually need it then file a bug report.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td> </td>
                           <td/>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">report:part</td>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">This property tells us which part of the model to gerenate.<para/>There is a corresponding stylesheet parameter named <emphasis role="bold">part</emphasis>.<para/>The documentation by default will recursively contain all elements in folders below the marked model/folder (see also the noroot stylesheet parameter).</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td> </td>
                           <td/>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">report:role</td>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">This parameter is to restrict the visibility of some parts of the model, based on the target audience.<para/>There is a corresponding stylesheet parameter named <emphasis role="bold">role</emphasis>.<para/>The objects and/or folders marked with report:role will be generated only if the stylesheet parameter's value is the same as the property's value.<para/>It is not possible to use more than one role neither as a property nor as a stylesheet parameter. If you would need this, please file a bug report.<para/>If you also want to handle diagrams properly, you have to utilize the split xml stylesheet.<para/>There is a corresponding xml tag to mark parts of the element documentation named <emphasis role="bold">only</emphasis>, with the <emphasis role="bold">role</emphasis> attribute, used in the obvious way.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td> </td>
                           <td/>
                        </tr>
                     </table>
                  </section>
