            <section id="2. Metamodels">
               <title>2. Metamodels</title>
               <para>Every model have some ontology as a background. In a lot of cases it is implicit, but there are cases when it is better to define it exactly. For example a well defined ontology is the basis for any model driven code/configuration generation.<para/>Another case is when you want to check your or others' work for mistakes and omissions.<para/>These cases need a well-defined set of rules about the subject matter. The ontology is captured in Archi as a metamodel, and based on it a policy is generated. The policy is then used by the rich export functionality to emit warnings about nonconformances, and to export the model in a way which is easily used by stylesheets to generate the necessary data.</para>
               <section id="1. Defining a metamodel">
                  <title>1. Defining a metamodel</title>
                  <para>The current way to define the metamodel is not considered to be the final one, however most probably I will keep this method as well. In the future metamodels will be defined by template diagrams, where the relations of a template object will define its attributes and the way the attributes obtain their value. Also the extension methods defined by Archimate 2.0 will be fully taken into account. The concepts are already very similar (maybe v2.0 was partly modeled by the Extended Archimate concept, see the history section), but I yet to check that the standard is actually followed.<para/>The core concept of the metamodel is objectClass. The objectClass tells us that we are facing a specialisation of an Archimate object (or any object defined by Archi, like Folder or model). As an example, we can have an Application Service with the objectClass <emphasis role="bold">WebService</emphasis>. In the metamodel level an objectclass have a parent (a built-in objectclass or a descendant thereof), and maybe some attributes. The attributes themselves have various properties, which may have default values.<para/>In the next sections we figure out how to define the objectClass for an Archimate object, and we learn how to define a metamodel.</para>
                  <section id="1. Ways to define the objectClass">
                     <title>1. Ways to define the objectClass</title>
                     <para/>
                     <table class="elementtable">
                        <tr>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">define the objectClass by direct property</td>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">An objectClass can be directly defined for an element by setting an <emphasis role="bold">objectClass</emphasis> property with the value as the objectClass name</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td> </td>
                           <td/>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">define the objectClass by indirect property</td>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">Any property having a <emphasis role="bold">:</emphasis> in its name implies that the string before the <emphasis role="bold">:</emphasis> is the objectClass of the containing element.<para/>For example by setting <emphasis role="bold">report:part</emphasis> to <emphasis role="bold">all</emphasis> on a folder, we actually telling that the folder have a <emphasis role="bold">report</emphasis> objectClass, and a report specific attribute named <emphasis role="bold">part</emphasis> with the value <emphasis role="bold">all</emphasis>.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td> </td>
                           <td/>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">define the objectClass by specialisation</td>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">this does not work yet.<para/>If object A is of the objectClass <emphasis role="bold">Template</emphasis> then all objects which specialisation of A will have the objectClass named after the name of A.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td> </td>
                           <td/>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">define the objectClass with a Group or Folder</td>
                           <td class="starter" valign="top">By setting the associatedObjectClass property of a Group or a Folder, we declare that all elements in it are belonging to the objectClass named by the value of the property.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                           <td> </td>
                           <td/>
                        </tr>
                     </table>
                  </section>
                  <section id="2. policy related objectClasses">
