               <section id="2. Creating a policy, checking policy conformance, quick export for xml-aware tools">
                  <title>2. Creating a policy, checking policy conformance, quick export for xml-aware tools</title>
                  <para>You need policy.style for that. It uses the "built-in" policy (generated from this model) to generate a policy named "policy.xml" in the target directory, then uses the generated policy on the model, exporting "archirich.xml" <link xlink:href="objectlist.html"
                           xrefstyle="what?"
                           href="objectlist.html">an object list</link> in html and docbook format, and a couple of cvs files in the csvdir directory.<para/>Any policy violation is logged as an error. As an example running policy.style in this model should result in exactly one error in both rounds; there is a deliberate omission in the model to show this feature. You can click on the log and it navigates you to the offending element.<para/>The file "archirich.xml" will contain elements for each instances of extended archimate objects. These elements are named after the objectClass's name, and contain one element for each of the attributes: the informations are already assembled (maybe from parts of the model far away from each other) for use by xml-aware tools.<para/>An example of such xml-aware tools is the xslts running in the next step, creating the objectlist docbook and html files contain the list of objects, as well as csv files for each objectClass.<para/>If you need anything more (for example harsher error handling) just drop a bug report.</para>
               </section>
            </section>
         </section>
         <section id="3. Create a report">
            <title>3. Create a report</title>
            <para/>
            <table class="elementtable">
               <tr>
                  <td colspan="2">
                     <figure>
                        <title>Create a report</title>
                        <remark/>
                        <mediaobject>
                           <imageobject>
                              <imagedata fileref="pics/3f087392.png"/>
                           </imageobject>
                        </mediaobject>
                     </figure>
                  </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Create a report</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">You want to configure the style used and maybe the output dir before you do this.<para/>You use the Styled Export menu entry.<para/>If you did not check "Don't ask for location", then a file dialog wil appear, where you can define the output directory.<para/>If the directory already exists (and you did not check the "Don't ask for location" checkbox), a dialog will appear asking whether to overwrite it.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Edit your model</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">You do it in the usual way in Archi.<para/>See <link xlink:href="http://archi.cetis.ac.uk/download/latest/Archi%20User%20Guide.pdf"
                           xrefstyle="what?"
                           href="http://archi.cetis.ac.uk/download/latest/Archi%20User%20Guide.pdf">http://archi.cetis.ac.uk/download/latest/Archi%20User%20Guide.pdf</link>
                  </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Preview output</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Using the browser you can preview the report.<para/>Just point to index.html in the output dir.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Preview the export log</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">The export log appearsh in an eventlog window. It is most useful if you have a policy related to the report. You can use it to remediate inconsitencies in your model. Clicking on the links will focus on the element which have the problem.<para/>Hint: By clicking analysis on the properties tab, you will see the views where the element participates in, and the relations of it. You can navigate to the view by clicking on it.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
            </table>
         </section>
         <section id="4. Troubleshooting">
            <title>4. Troubleshooting</title>
            <para/>
            <table class="elementtable">
               <tr>
                  <td colspan="2">
                     <figure>
                        <title>Troubleshooting</title>
                        <remark/>
                        <mediaobject>
                           <imageobject>
                              <imagedata fileref="pics/12cc0a0a.png"/>
                           </imageobject>
                        </mediaobject>
                     </figure>
                  </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Analyse problem</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">You can look at several places to figure out what have happened.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Being happy</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Problem solved, congratulation.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Look at the application log</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">See application log file for the location of application log file.<para/>Look at the end of it for any hint.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Look at the problem report dialog</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">The problem report dialog should give you some hint on what happened</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">No clue</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">If you don't know what caused the problem, or how to solve this, it is time to report it.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Problem identified</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">If you could identify the cause of the problem, you are happy.<para/>Now the next step is to remediate or report the problem.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Problem occured</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">
                     <para/>If there is something wrong in the process, a problem report dialog will appear.<para/>See Troubleshooting for this case.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">Remediate problem</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">If you can remediate the problem (e.g. it is a problem with a stylesheet or policy you have created, or there is a known workaround for a known bug),<para/>you do it, and you became very happy.<para/>If the fix needs something more (it is an unknown bug, or needs a yet unknown fix or change in the source code), please report it.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">application log file</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">In the installation directory of Archi there is a file called Archi.ini<para/>Look at the definition of osgi.instance.area, looking something like this:<para/>-Dosgi.instance.area=@user.home/uk.ac.bolton/Archi<para/>The @user.home here is your home directory.<para/>Within the directory defined by osgi.instance.area there is a file called .metadata/.log<para/>This is the log file.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">look at stdout/stderr</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">If still no solution, look at the stdout/stderr of the application.<para/>In unix, you should start it from a terminal window to achieve it, or look at the .xsession-error or similar file. See the configuration of your desktop for further details.<para/>In windows? Dunno.</td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">report problem</td>
                  <td class="starter" valign="top">You can report any problem through <link xlink:href="https://sourceforge.net/p/archistyledhtml/tickets/"
                           xrefstyle="what?"
                           href="https://sourceforge.net/p/archistyledhtml/tickets/">https://sourceforge.net/p/archistyledhtml/tickets/</link> 
                  </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                  <td> </td>
                  <td/>
               </tr>
            </table>
         </section>
