      <section id="6. history">
         <title>6. history</title>
         <para/>
         <section id="Extended Archimate">
            <title>Extended Archimate</title>
            <para>The Archimate 2 standard have introduced methods to extend the underlying metamodel of Archimate.<para/>The StyledHtml module will go along these lines.<para/>For historical purposes you can find my proposal from Archimate 1 times here:<para/>This is a proposal for an extension to Archimate methodology, adding a metamodel layer in the following way:<para/>- Instances of Archimate objects can have properties. This extension is already implemented in Archi.<para/>- There is a 4th layer above the well-known ones: the ontology/metamodel layer, describing concepts derived from core archimate concepts, and the properties associated with that concept.<para/>- A new concept of the ontology should be either a simple one, or a composite one. There are the following constraints to derive concepts of an ontology:<para/> - A simple concept should be derived from a core concept of the Archimate ontology.<para/> - A composite concept is a structure built from simple concepts. A composite concept is a "macro": it is defined by and can always be replaced with a structure of simple concepts, and all properties of the composite concept can be bound to a simple concept in the underlying structure.<para/>As you can see Extended Archimate is not another arbitrary methodology, because:<para/>- A model described in the extended archimate methodology can always be described in the core archimate methodology. Moreover a model described in ontology B can be described in ontology A, if B is derived from A.<para/>- Because of the above, all reasoning which holds for the core archimate methodology will hold for any ontology B based on it. Moreover for each ontology A, and B where B is derived from A, all reasoning for A will hold for B.<para/>- If there would be a methodology which incompatible with archimate - in the sense that models using that methodology cannot be meaningfully described in archimate - it would not be describeable in the extended methodology either (but archimate is capable to describe everything, so it is merely a theoretical point:).<para/>- Models using other methodology could be described by first defining the ontology of the other methodology in EA ontology layer, making archimate the mother of all methodologies:)<para/>Reasoning for the necessity of EA:<para/>Archimate right now is a closed ontology. It does have a lot of advantages, and EA would not loose any of them, because any model in EA should have a representation in the core ontology. But a closed ontology is not capable to describe our world in the necessary detail . When you start any design work, the first step is to create a view of the world around you. Let's take a sentence from the standard itself to illustrate it: "Examples of business actors are humans, departments, and business units." So to have the descriptive power, the ontology should be open "downward".<para/>This means that archimate as it is would not be able to support a design beyond a point. The more you focus only on some aspects of the world, the deeper you can go using Archimate, but it comes with the cost that you should neglect other aspects, otherwise they would interfere with your model. And there is invariably a point where another methodology should be used, and the model you built can no longer fully serve the purpose of being a reference point. When you gave your model to a developer and he should rebuild it in UML (or just don't have a frame of thought to develop your model further), it is not just a waste of effort, but makes communication harder because the differing views on the world. For us security people who should care with all the layers and from the conception to the details, this is a nightmare.<para/>With extended archimate the whole development cycle would be traceable in one model, refining not just the model but the ontology with it as development progresses. This makes automated checks for model structure and content reasonable, and even generation of code and configuration is possible. This not just gives the opportunity to help the uninitiated to make quality work, and give the tedious work to machines, but also helps traceability across the different levels of detail. If you ever tried to figure out whether a high-level requirement is fully implemented across a complex system, you will know what I am talking about. </para>
         </section>
      </section>
