         <section id="repository of servers and systems">
            <title>repository of servers and systems</title>
            <para>See <link xlink:href="objectlist.html#Server"
                     xrefstyle="what?"
                     href="objectlist.html#Server">the Server list</link>, the <link xlink:href="objectlist.html#Application"
                     xrefstyle="what?"
                     href="objectlist.html#Application">the Application list</link>, and the <link xlink:href="objectlist.html#ApplicationCollection"
                     xrefstyle="what?"
                     href="objectlist.html#ApplicationCollection">The ApplicationCollection list</link>.<para/>For the details, see the section about metamodels. <para/>On Monday, 31 January 2011 23:26:06 UTC+1, TerChris wrote:<para/>    Hi<para/>    First of all I’m pleased to find a tool that I think will help me in creating a repository of servers, systems and the dependencies between them.<para/>    I was on a project earlier where we used www.troux.com Architect (ver8). Troux Architect is not a cheap tool and we cannot justify the cost of it on the project I’m working at now.<para/>    I want to do the same as I did in the “troux-project”. That is to create a repository of all servers, systems, dependencies and the people responsible for running/administering/developing each item.<para/>    I want to model this structure.<para/>    Server attributes:<para/>    PhysicalHardware (eg the physical server)<para/>    Location (where the PhysicalHardware is placed)<para/>    ServerName (the name of the server)<para/>    IP Address<para/>    Status (In preparation, In Test, In production, Under liquidation, Liquidated)<para/>    NetworkZone (what network zone the server is placed)<para/>    OperatingSystem (what OS it runs)<para/>    ServerRole (Application server, File Server…)<para/>    TechnicalContact (Name of person)<para/>    Application attributes: (a application or system)<para/>    ApplicationName (name of the system)<para/>    TechnicalContact (Name of person)<para/>    AdmContact (Name of person)<para/>    Application collection: (A collection of applications/systems that belong together eg Sallary payment)<para/>    CollectionName (name of the collection of applications)<para/>    AdmContact (Name of person)<para/>    I then want to create a model view for each Application collection that shows:<para/>    What applications the collection consists of.<para/>    What dependencies there are between the applications in the collection and to applications outside the collection.<para/>    What servers the applications run on<para/>    What PhysicalHardware the servers run on (physical or a vmware)<para/>    Is this possible using Archi?<para/>    I can’t see a way to add more properties to a device. Is it not possible?<para/>    Regards<para/>    Terje</para>
